Dear Hiring Team,

It is with great pleasure that I submit my candidacy for the *Software Engineer, Backend* with *Setpoint*. I bring over three years of professional experience building backend systems, distributed platforms, and production-grade APIs, along with a strong academic foundation as a Master of Science in Computer Science graduate from Pace University, NY.

Through my experience across two engineering roles, I have built and delivered production-grade backend systems that directly reflect the full-stack Python ownership and rapid-iteration culture this role demands. As a Software Engineer at Sperse, I owned and built a multi-agent CRM platform end-to-end using Python, FastAPI, and LangGraph, serving 10,000+ users — iterating rapidly on routing logic and agent schemas through tight customer-feedback loops that kept our product aligned with real usage. Alongside it, I engineered a FastMCP server exposing 160+ Python backend actions as LLM-callable tools, investing directly in developer experience by reducing the time engineers spent wiring new workflows and providing built-in monitoring with tenant-aware access control. To keep these systems production-ready under rapid prototyping cycles, I built GitHub Actions CI/CD pipelines with OpenTelemetry trace-based evals that gate every deployment — scoring latency, accuracy, and safety regressions before merging. I also owned full product feature development of a React Flow and TypeScript visual workflow platform with Temporal for durable, resumable execution — demonstrating the end-to-end feature ownership that Setpoint values in its engineers. Prior to Sperse, as a Software Engineer at Qualitest, I contributed to backbone infrastructure users relied on daily. I designed and owned a cloud-agnostic Storage Service in Java and Spring Boot with PostgreSQL and Redis that seamlessly handled file operations across AWS S3, Google Cloud Storage, and MinIO via expiring signed URLs, and orchestrated long-running jobs with AWS Step Functions to eliminate Lambda timeouts and improve error recovery across 100K+ weekly executions — work that demanded the systems-level reliability thinking needed to make transactions instant and error-free. Together, these roles have prepared me to own end-to-end backend features and invest in developer tooling that keeps Setpoint's engineering team moving fast.

Beyond my professional roles, my academic work and independent projects have sharpened my ability to tackle complex distributed systems from first principles — skills that translate directly into the cross-functional collaboration and technical communication this role values. As a graduate student at Pace University, I designed the Dark Factory distributed coding-agent orchestrator, which breaks large coding requests into dependency-aware task DAGs and executes them across multi-machine agents with retries and timeout handling — a project that deepened my understanding of orchestration, fault tolerance, and the kind of rigorous system design that underpins reliable financial infrastructure. This work has shaped me into an engineer who builds with care and validates with evidence, both of which I would bring to Setpoint's mission.

I have always been passionate about making credit transactions instant and error-free, and building trust in the financial system, and envision myself contributing my talent to the furthering of modernizing the infrastructure behind private credit and asset-backed lending. I would love to discuss my interest in this position with your team and can be reached at #ph or #eml. Thank you for your time and consideration, I look forward to connecting!

